The lex Pompeia confined the term to the killing of ascendants, husbands, wives, consobrini, stepfathers and stepmothers, fathers· and mothers·in-law, patrons and descendants, except the killing of a son by his father, Dig. 48. 9. 1. Hadrian sentenced a man who killed his son to deportatio, Dig. ib. 5, but this was not included under parricide till the time of Constantine, p. 117 supr.
